

bash — obviously, you already depend on it. Use 5.x if possible (most modern macOS/Linux have 5.x or 5.1).

coreutils — GNU core utilities for things like ls, cat, cut, date, sort.

sed, awk — text processing, very stable and cross-platform.

grep / egrep — essential for filtering.

find / xargs — file operations.

mkdir, rm, cp, mv — file management.


jq — extremely reliable for parsing/manipulating JSON in Bash.

yq — YAML parsing (if you ever move to YAML configs).

Python json module — native, zero-install for JSON tasks in Python scripts.

python3 — needed for more complex logic; most modern systems ship with Python 3.10+.



3️⃣ Terminal Enhancements / UI

tput / terminfo — terminal control, colors, cursor movement.

ncurses — foundation for TUIs, via Python curses module or Bash wrappers.

dialog / whiptail — simple menus, multi-select dialogs.

fzf — interactive fuzzy finder; extremely stable and widely used.

bat — enhanced cat with syntax highlighting (optional, fallback to cat).


4️⃣ File & Data Compression / Transport

gzip, bzip2, xz — compress logs or data.

rsync — robust file sync between folders, portable for backups.

curl / wget — for future optional online interactions.

openssl — for secure hashing, encryption.


5️⃣ Dependency Management & Virtualization

pyenv / venv — manage Python versions for microservices.

brew / apt / dnf — package installation in setup scripts.

asdf — multi-language version manager if you later integrate other languages.

6️⃣ Optional but Highly Useful Utilities

tree — visualize directories.

htop / glances — system monitoring if you add resource-sensitive services.

uuidgen — generate UUIDs for microservice IDs.

dateutils — advanced date calculations.

7️⃣ Recommended Python Packages (for scripting)

For Python microservices:

click — building CLI commands with subcommands; lightweight and robust.

rich — colorful output, tables, progress bars.

pyyaml — if YAML configs are needed.

pydantic — for structured data validation (optional for microservices).

tabulate — tables in terminal.

requests — if optional HTTP interactions appear later.

8️⃣ General Recommendations

Stick to POSIX utilities where possible — ensures compatibility on macOS, Linux, BSD.

Limit external dependencies to widely-available, stable, and maintained tools (jq, fzf, python3) so setup is smooth.

Optional features can have fallbacks — e.g., if bat isn’t installed, fallback to cat.

Test on clean macOS / Linux environments — ensures you don’t accidentally rely on dev-installed tools.